body:
A Solidity contract is like a class that lives permanently on the blockchain. It has state variables (data stored on-chain, costs gas to change) and functions (code that reads or writes that data).

EXAMPLE:
pragma solidity ^0.8.20;

contract Counter {
    uint256 public count; // state variable, stored on-chain

    function increment() public {
        count += 1; // this costs gas
    }

    function getCount() public view returns (uint256) {
        return count; // 'view' = reads only, free to call
    }
}

WHY IT MATTERS: Every state change costs real money (gas). Understanding that state variables persist on-chain -- and that reading them is free but writing costs gas -- shapes almost every design decision you'll make.

FURTHER READING:
- Solidity docs, Structure of a Contract: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/structure-of-a-contract.html
- Ethereum.org, Intro to smart contracts: https://ethereum.org/en/developers/docs/smart-contracts/

