body:
Solidity has value types (uint, int, bool, address, bytes32) that are cheap, and reference types (arrays, structs, mappings, strings) that need a data location: storage, memory, or calldata.

- storage: permanent, on-chain, expensive
- memory: temporary, exists only during function execution, cheaper
- calldata: read-only, used for external function inputs, cheapest

EXAMPLE:
function sumArray(uint256[] calldata nums) external pure returns (uint256) {
    uint256 total; // memory by default for value types
    for (uint256 i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
        total += nums[i];
    }
    return total;
}

WHY IT MATTERS: Picking the wrong data location is one of the most common beginner mistakes, and it directly affects gas cost -- sometimes by 10x or more. Using calldata instead of memory for external function array/string parameters alone can meaningfully cut gas.

FURTHER READING:
- Solidity docs, Data Location: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/types.html#data-location
- CoinsBench guide (community): https://coinsbench.com

