body:
Events let contracts write cheap, indexed logs to the blockchain that off-chain apps (like a frontend or The Graph) can listen for. They're much cheaper than storage for data that just needs to be recorded, not read on-chain again.

EXAMPLE:
event Transfer(address indexed from, address indexed to, uint256 amount);

function transfer(address to, uint256 amount) external {
    balances[msg.sender] -= amount;
    balances[to] += amount;
    emit Transfer(msg.sender, to, amount);
}

WHY IT MATTERS: Contracts themselves can't read their own past events -- events are for the outside world. Every token transfer, NFT mint, and DEX swap you've ever seen on Etherscan was picked up via an event log.

FURTHER READING:
- Solidity docs, Events: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/contracts.html#events
- Ethereum.org, Events and Logging: https://ethereum.org/en/developers/tutorials/logging-events-smart-contracts/

