body:
Modifiers wrap reusable logic (like access checks) around functions. The 'onlyOwner' pattern is the most common access control scheme in Solidity, and OpenZeppelin's Ownable is the industry-standard implementation.

EXAMPLE:
contract AccessControlled {
    address public owner;

    constructor() {
        owner = msg.sender; // deployer becomes the owner
    }

    modifier onlyOwner() {
        require(msg.sender == owner, "Not owner");
        _; // this underscore is where the function body runs
    }

    function withdraw() external onlyOwner {
        (bool success, ) = owner.call{value: address(this).balance}("");
        require(success, "Transfer failed");
    }
}

// In production, prefer OpenZeppelin's audited Ownable instead of
// writing this pattern by hand:
// import "@openzeppelin/contracts/access/Ownable.sol";
// contract AccessControlled is Ownable {
//     constructor() Ownable(msg.sender) {}
// }

WHY IT MATTERS: Missing or broken access control is one of the top causes of exploited contracts historically. Note this example also uses .call{value: ...}("") instead of the older .transfer() -- .transfer() only forwards a fixed 2300 gas, which breaks with contract wallets that need more. Always use a battle-tested library (OpenZeppelin's Ownable) rather than writing this from scratch for production code.

FURTHER READING:
- OpenZeppelin Ownable docs: https://docs.openzeppelin.com/contracts/access-control
- Solidity docs, Function Modifiers: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/contracts.html#function-modifiers

