msg.sender is the address that called the current function. msg.value is the amount of ETH (in wei) sent with the call. A function must be marked 'payable' to receive ETH at all.

EXAMPLE:
mapping(address => uint256) public deposits;

function deposit() external payable {
    require(msg.value > 0, "Send some ETH");
    deposits[msg.sender] += msg.value;
}

WHY IT MATTERS: msg.sender is the foundation of on-chain identity and authentication -- there's no login system, just 'whoever signed this transaction.' Forgetting 'payable' is a classic beginner error that makes a function reject any ETH sent to it.

