body:
Every operation on Ethereum costs 'gas' -- a unit measuring computational effort. You pay gas_used * gas_price in ETH. Storage writes are the most expensive operation; reads and simple math are cheap.

Common optimizations:
- Pack multiple small variables (uint8, bool) into one storage slot
- Use calldata instead of memory for external function params
- Cache storage reads in memory inside loops
- Use custom errors instead of require strings (cheaper since Solidity 0.8.4)

EXAMPLE:
error InsufficientBalance(uint256 available, uint256 required);

function withdraw(uint256 amt) external {
    if (balances[msg.sender] < amt) {
        revert InsufficientBalance(balances[msg.sender], amt);
    }
}

WHY IT MATTERS: Gas costs are real money paid by your users. A poorly optimized contract can make a simple action cost 5-10x more than it needs to.

FURTHER READING:
- Solidity docs, Gas Optimization: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/internals/optimizer.html
- ConsenSys, Gas Optimization Techniques: https://consensys.io/blog

