ERC-721 represents unique, non-fungible tokens -- each tokenId is distinct, unlike ERC-20 where all units are interchangeable. Core functions: ownerOf, balanceOf, transferFrom, approve, and a tokenURI for metadata.

EXAMPLE (using OpenZeppelin, the standard approach):
import "@openzeppelin/contracts/token/ERC721/ERC721.sol";

contract MyNFT is ERC721 {
    uint256 public nextTokenId;

    constructor() ERC721("MyNFT", "MNFT") {}

    function mint() external {
        _safeMint(msg.sender, nextTokenId);
        nextTokenId++;
    }
}

WHY IT MATTERS: 'NFT' just means 'this standard interface plus a metadata URI' -- the JSON metadata (image, traits) usually lives off-chain (IPFS or a server), not on the blockchain itself. This is a common source of confusion for newcomers.

FURTHER READING:
- EIP-721 spec: https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-721
- OpenZeppelin ERC721 docs: https://docs.openzeppelin.com/contracts/erc721

