body:
Before Solidity 0.8.0, uint256 math would silently wrap around (e.g. 0 - 1 became a huge number instead of erroring). Solidity 0.8+ reverts automatically on overflow/underflow, which removed an entire class of bugs by default.

EXAMPLE:
// Solidity 0.8+: this reverts automatically if balance < amount
function withdraw(uint256 amount) external {
    balances[msg.sender] -= amount; // safe by default now
}

// To intentionally allow wrapping (rare, gas-sensitive cases):
function wrappingSub(uint256 a, uint256 b) external pure returns (uint256) {
    unchecked {
        return a - b; // no revert, old behavior
    }
}

WHY IT MATTERS: Before this language-level fix, developers had to manually use libraries like SafeMath for every arithmetic operation. If you see SafeMath in older code, it's now largely unnecessary on 0.8+.

FURTHER READING:
- Solidity docs, 0.8.0 release notes: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/080-breaking-changes.html
- Solidity docs, Checked/Unchecked Arithmetic: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/control-structures.html#checked-or-unchecked-arithmetic

