body:
Contracts can inherit from other contracts (reusing their functions/state) and implement interfaces (a contract's public function signatures with no implementation, used for interoperability).

EXAMPLE:
interface IERC20 {
    function transfer(address to, uint256 amount) external returns (bool);
}

contract Base {
    function greet() public pure virtual returns (string memory) {
        return "Hello";
    }
}

contract Child is Base {
    function greet() public pure override returns (string memory) {
        return "Hi from Child";
    }
}

WHY IT MATTERS: Interfaces are how contracts you've never seen the source code for can still interact safely -- e.g. any DEX can call transfer() on any ERC-20 token because they all implement the same interface.

FURTHER READING:
- Solidity docs, Inheritance: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/contracts.html#inheritance
- Solidity docs, Interfaces: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/contracts.html#interfaces

