body:
- require(condition, "msg"): checks input/conditions, refunds remaining gas, most common
- revert("msg"): manually stop execution, same effect as a failed require
- assert(condition): should NEVER fail in correct code -- signals a bug, consumes all gas (rarely used now)
- custom errors (0.8.4+): cheaper than string-based require, recommended for gas-conscious code

EXAMPLE:
error NotEnoughFunds(uint256 have, uint256 want);

function pay(uint256 amount) external {
    if (balance < amount) revert NotEnoughFunds(balance, amount);
    // ...
}

WHY IT MATTERS: Choosing the right error mechanism affects both gas cost and how clearly your contract communicates failures to frontends and other developers integrating with it.

FURTHER READING:
- Solidity docs, Error Handling: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/control-structures.html#error-handling-assert-require-revert-and-exceptions

