A constructor runs exactly once, at deployment, and is used to set initial state (like an owner or token name). Once deployed, a contract's code is immutable by default -- you can't edit it, only deploy a new one.

EXAMPLE:
contract Token {
    address public owner;
    string public name;

    constructor(string memory _name) {
        owner = msg.sender;
        name = _name;
    }
}

WHY IT MATTERS: Immutability is both smart contracts' biggest strength (trustless, tamper-proof) and biggest risk (a bug deployed is a bug forever, unless you built in an upgrade mechanism in advance).

FURTHER READING:
- Solidity docs, Constructors: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/contracts.html#constructors
- Ethereum.org, Deploying smart contracts: https://ethereum.org/en/developers/docs/smart-contracts/deploying/

