receive() runs when a contract gets plain ETH with no data attached. fallback() runs when a call doesn't match any function signature (or as a catch-all if receive doesn't exist). Both are optional but important for contracts meant to hold ETH.

EXAMPLE:
contract Wallet {
    event Received(address sender, uint256 amount);

    receive() external payable {
        emit Received(msg.sender, msg.value);
    }

    fallback() external payable {
        // catches calls to non-existent functions
    }
}

WHY IT MATTERS: Without a receive() function, a plain ETH transfer (like from a wallet's 'send' button) to your contract will simply fail and revert -- a very common beginner surprise.

