body:
Since deployed contract code is immutable, 'upgradeability' is faked using proxy patterns: a lightweight Proxy contract holds the storage and forwards calls via delegatecall to a separate Logic contract, which CAN be swapped out.

Simplified idea:
contract Proxy {
    address public implementation;

    fallback() external payable {
        (bool ok, ) = implementation.delegatecall(msg.data);
        require(ok);
    }
}

delegatecall runs the logic contract's code but uses the PROXY's storage -- that's the trick that makes upgrades possible.

WHY IT MATTERS: Proxy patterns are powerful but notoriously easy to get wrong (storage slot collisions, uninitialized implementations). Always use OpenZeppelin's audited Upgrades plugin rather than hand-rolling this.

FURTHER READING:
- OpenZeppelin, Proxy Upgrade Pattern: https://docs.openzeppelin.com/upgrades-plugins/proxies
- OpenZeppelin, Writing Upgradeable Contracts: https://docs.openzeppelin.com/upgrades-plugins/writing-upgradeable

