Smart contracts can only see on-chain data -- they have no native way to know a stock price, weather, or off-chain event outcome. Oracles are services (like Chainlink) that bring external data on-chain in a decentralized, tamper-resistant way.

EXAMPLE (Chainlink price feed pattern):
import "@chainlink/contracts/src/v0.8/interfaces/AggregatorV3Interface.sol";

AggregatorV3Interface internal priceFeed;

function getLatestPrice() public view returns (int256) {
    (, int256 price, , , ) = priceFeed.latestRoundData();
    return price;
}

WHY IT MATTERS: 'Just check an API' isn't possible in Solidity -- there's no native HTTP request. Any DeFi protocol using real-world prices (lending, derivatives) depends entirely on oracle security; oracle manipulation is a leading cause of DeFi exploits.

FURTHER READING:
- Chainlink docs, What is an oracle: https://docs.chain.link/architecture-overview/architecture-decentralized-model
- Ethereum.org, Oracles: https://ethereum.org/en/developers/docs/oracles/

