body:
Storage is organized in 32-byte slots. If you declare multiple small variables (uint8, uint16, bool) next to each other in a struct, Solidity can pack them into a single slot -- saving significant gas versus each taking its own slot.

EXAMPLE:
// Wasteful: 3 separate storage slots
struct Bad {
    uint256 a; // full slot
    uint8 b;   // own slot
    uint256 c; // full slot
}

// Efficient: b packs alongside a's slot boundary
struct Good {
    uint128 a;
    uint128 b; // packs with 'a' into one slot
    uint256 c;
}

WHY IT MATTERS: Storage writes are the single most expensive EVM operation. Thoughtful struct ordering is a simple, free optimization that can meaningfully cut deployment and usage costs.

FURTHER READING:
- Solidity docs, Layout of State Variables: https://docs.soliditylang.org/en/latest/internals/layout_in_storage.html

